{
    "discussion": {
        "agreements": [
            "All evaluators recognized that results 1, 7, and 11 were highly relevant, as they directly addressed New Frontiers-class Uranus orbiter mission concepts closely aligned with the goals and methodology of the main paper.",
            "There was agreement that results focused on unrelated missions (e.g., 3, 17, 20) or different mission classes (e.g., 4, 8, 10, 19) were not relevant to the main paper's specific scope.",
            "All evaluators acknowledged the importance of the broader scientific context and rationale for Uranus exploration provided by some results (e.g., 5, 9, 12, 13)."
        ],
        "disagreements": [
            "There were differing opinions on the relevance of results discussing atmospheric probes (6, 18), with Claude and Gemini considering them relevant due to their alignment with the scientific goals, while DeepSeek viewed them as diverging from the main paper's orbiter-centric methodology.",
            "Claude and Gemini disagreed on the relevance of result 9, with Claude considering it relevant due to its discussion of ice giant magnetospheres (a key science goal), while Gemini viewed it as only tangentially relevant since it did not address the mission concept or design.",
            "There were different perspectives on the relevance of mission concepts from other space agencies (e.g., 15, 19), with Gemini and DeepSeek considering them less relevant due to their divergence from the NASA New Frontiers program focus."
        ],
        "key_insights": [
            "The evaluations highlighted the importance of focusing on results that specifically address New Frontiers-class mission concepts and feasibility studies, as these are most closely aligned with the main paper's objectives.",
            "Several evaluators noted the value of results that provide detailed technical analysis and trade-off discussions related to instrument selection, mission design, and cost constraints.",
            "The broader scientific context and rationale for Uranus exploration, while not directly addressing the main paper's methodology, were recognized as important supporting information."
        ],
        "suggested_focus": [
            "Further discussion is needed on the relevance of atmospheric probe studies and whether they should be considered within the scope of the main paper's orbiter-centric focus.",
            "The group should discuss the level of relevance to assign to mission concepts from other space agencies or programs, and whether they offer valuable insights despite differences in mission class or scope.",
            "Evaluators should explore strategies for prioritizing results that provide detailed technical analyses and design trade-offs, as these are critical for assessing the feasibility and methodology of the QUEST mission concept."
        ]
    }
}
